st: Families in an Archaeology Museum -- tChapter 13 Small People versus Big Heritage -- tPart IV. Contexts of Telling III: Schools and Special Classrooms -- tChapter 14 Landscapes and Winter Counts: Lakota Ways of Telling Children About the Past -- tChapter 15 Telling Children About the Past in Brazil -- tChapter 16 From Fragments to Contexts: Teaching Prehistory to Village Children in Romania0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book brings together archeologists, historians, psychologists, and educators from different countries and academic traditions to address the many ways that we tell children about the (distant) past. Knowing the past is fundamentally important for human societies, as well as for individual development. The authors expose many unquestioned assumptions and preformed images in narratives of the past that are routinely presented to children. The contributors both examine the ways in which children come to grips with the past and critically assess the many ways in which contemporary societies and an increasing number of commercial agents construct and use the past.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aAntiquities, PrehistoricxStudy and teaching. 0aArchaeology and historyxStudy and teaching. 0aArchaeologyxStudy and teaching. 0aPrehistoric peoplesxStudy and teaching. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Archaeology.2bisacsh  aArchaeology and Children.  aIndividual Development.  aTeaching History.  aTeaching the Past.  aUse of the Past.1 aBauer, Patricia J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBinant, Pascale, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoulotis, Christos, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCostall, Alan, econtribut